&lt;p&gt;
	Greenore as we see it today was built by the London North Western Railway Company as a railway terminal and ferry port. The construction was completed and offically opened by Earl Spencer the Lord Lieutenant of Ireland on the 30th of April 1873 after four years of building and at a cost of 153,000 pounds. Prior to this the village was only a cluster of small houses just to the South East of the present village.&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;br /&gt;
	Named Grianphort or haven/port of the sun because the area gets uninterupted sun from early morning as the sun rises on the Eastern horizon and uniquely for the area the sun still shines on us until late in the evening when the sun sets over Newry at the N/W end of Carlingford Lough.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.iguidecarlingfordmourne.com/WEBFILES/images/birdslanapart2.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 262px; height: 168px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	The Cooley and Mourne Mountains provide shelter from Southerly through Northerly winds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.iguidecarlingfordmourne.com/WEBFILES/images/birdslaneapart1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 262px; height: 168px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	We are unique because the rest of Lough shores are in the shade of the mountains from early in the evening.&lt;/p&gt;

